description.narrative: The Project Development Objective (PDO) is to increase coverage of essential health services of adequate quality, with a focus on maternal, newborn and child health (MNCH), and, in the event of an Eligible Crisis or Emergency, to provide immediate and effective response to said Eligible Crisis or Emergency.

condition.narrative: Finance Agreement :Contingent Emergency Response | Description : The Recipient shall adopt a satisfactory Contingent EmergencyResponse Implementation Plan for Component 3 of the Project and, in the event of an eligible crisis or emergency, ensure that theactivities under said component are carried out in accordance with such plan and all relevant safeguard requirements. Frequency:CONTINUOUS

Finance Agreement :Environmental and Social Safeguards | Description :The Recipient shall ensure that the Project is carried out inaccordance with the provisions of the Environmental Management Plan and the Community Engagement Planning Framework and thesafeguard provisions of the Financing Agreement. | Frequency :CONTINUOUS

Finance Agreement :Financial Management staffing at township level | Description :The Recipient shall ensure that the Departmentsof Health and Health Planning of MOH, each Region/State Health Department and each Township Health Department has appointed staffat appropriate level, and with terms of reference and qualifications specified in theOperations Manual, to assist the saiddepartment in the carrying out of their financial management functions in accordance with the OM.Th | Due Date :31-Mar-2015

Finance Agreement :Independent Verification Agent | Description :Recipient shall appoint an independent Disbursement LinkedIndicator verification agent, with terms of reference and qualifications satisfactory to the Association. | Due Date :31-Mar-2016

Schedule 2 Section I.A.1. The Recipient shall maintain, at all times during the implementation of the Project, a Project oversightcommittee with functions, composition and resources satisfactory to the Association

Section F. Other UndertakingsIn order to ensure the sustainability of the heath service delivery infrastructure under Part 1 ofthe Project, the Recipient through MOHS shall provide adequate counterpart financing and human resources to support recurrent costsand staffing needs upon the completion of respective facilities.

Section I. A. 2. Institutional ArrangementsThe Recipient shall maintain, throughout the implementation of the Project, P-MOST atthe central level with functions, resources, and staff (including, inter alia, a designated Project Director and Project Managers)with qualifications and experience and in number acceptable to the Association.
Section I. B. The Recipient shall ensure that the Project is carried out in accordance with the arrangements and procedures set outin the Project Operations Manual.

Section I. D. the Recipient shall: (a) not later than December 1 of each year during the implementation of the Project, furnishreports to the Association on the status of achievement of the relevant DLI Targets; and (b) not later than January 31 of each yearduring the implementation of the Project, furnish to the Association the reports of the independent verification agent.

title.narrative: Townships in which the Township Health Departments have prepared an integrated and inclusive Township Health Plans (OC DLI#4)
Townships in which all rural health centers and atleast 50% of subcenters have been supervised at least twice in a fiscal year by Township Health Department using checklist (OC DLI#5)
Townships in which the township hospital and at least 60% of other Health Facilities have met a minimum readiness level of 14 out of 20 to provide essential MNCH services (OC DLI#1)
Townships in which atleast 80% of required number antenatal and postnatal visits and deliveries have been carried out by basic health staff (OC DLI#3)
Townships in which at least 60% of midwives have been trained to deliver BeMOC and IMCI (OC DLI#7)
Township in which township health department has been supervised at least twice in a fiscal year by State/Region Health Department officials using checklist (OC DLI#6)
Townships in which the township hospital and atleast 80% of other health facilities have received Health Facility Grants in accordance with Project Operations Manual (OC DLI#2)
Improved fund flows (recurrent) to front line health facilities--Training on guidelines developed
Improved supervision (supervision standards and checklists developed)
Essential Package of Health Services including quality standards defined, costed, approved, and publicly communicated
Health Financing Strategy for UHC developed, approved, and communicated
Health Care Waste Management guidelines and policy developed and implemented
People who have received essential health, nutrition, and population (HNP) services
Number of women and children who have received basic nutrition services
Number of deliveries attended by skilled health personnel
Children immunized of measles rubella at age of 9 months
Deliveries which are followed by adequate postnatal care within 2 days of birth
Deliveries with skilled birth attendant in Shan
Deliveries with skilled birth attendant in Ayeyarwady
ICT-based innovations in health piloted or scaled up
Beneficiary satisfaction with health services delivered in facilities selected for FFHSDI investment
Registered pregnancies in health facilities in selected townships
Electronic database system established at the union level for ministry-wide budget and expenditure tracking (AF DLI #5b)
Guidelines developed for Region/State multi-stakeholder annual planning and review meetings and Township biannual review meetings (AF DLI #4a)
Mapping of CBHWs in Ayeyarwady and Shan completed (AF DLI #2b)
Policy on CBHWs endorsed and disseminated by MOHS (AF DLI #2a)
Procurement and Supply Chain Management (PSCM) Operational Plan, including a performance monitoring framework, developed and approved (AF DLI #6a)
Quality readiness criteria developed and endorsed by MOHS (AF DLI #1b)
Sub-national level training conducted with finance staff from all 17 Regions/States on electronic budget implementation reporting system (AF DLI #5a)
Training curriculum of CBHWs updated (AF DLI #2c)
Training of trainers on Infection Prevention and Control (IPC) and Health Care Waste Management (HCWM) completed in all Regions/States (AF DLI #3a)
Training package for safe delivery and early essential newborn care and care for small babies and neonatal resuscitation updated (AF DLI #1a)
Grievance Redress Mechanism using ICT platform initiated
FFHSDI townships organizing multi-stakeholder biannual reviews and sharing meeting minutes with participants (AF DLI #4c)
Townships where 80% of relevant basic health staff have been trained in IPC, including HCWM (AF DLI #3b)
Regions/States with multi-stakeholder platform for Annual Planning and Review and meeting minutes shared with all participants (AF DLI #4b)
Region/State Health Departments and township health departments maintaining financial data in secure, designated computer system and sending electronic copies of budget execution reports (AF DLI #5c)
Villages in Ayeyarwady and Shan with at least one CBHW trained, registered, and equipped (AF DLI #2d)
PHC facilities with labor room in FFHSDI townships that meet readiness criteria per agreed checklist (AF DLI #1d)
Skilled birth attendants (SBAs) in Ayeyarwady Region and Shan State trained using the updated training package for essential MNCH care (AF DLI #1c)
MOHS Departments enter and analyze the annual budget and expenditure data (AF DLI #5d)
Townships where 100% of township hospitals and station hospitals are implementing IPC and HCWM, and 50% of rural health centers areimplementing HCWM (AF DLI #3c)
Region/State Health Departments with electronic Logistics Management Information Systems (AF DLI #6b)
FFHSDI townships preparing township health investment plan and receiving annual operational budget based on the plan (AF DLI #5e)
Township Health Investment Plans developed with engagement of community and involvement of ethnic providers and non-government organizations
Health facilities in selected townships that have been re-constructed or renovated, and equipped/ furnished to specified standard.
